Context()->normalStrings;

##############################################

ANS( $radio->cmp() );

##############################################

$y1=$right->eval(x=>1);

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

In [`[$left]=[$right]`], since the coefficient of [`x^{2}`] is negative, the parabola faces down.

For the quadratic function [`y=-x^{2}`], when [`x=1`], [`y=-1`]. The point on the parabola is [`(1,-1)`].

For the quadratic function [`[$left]=[$right]`], when [`x=1`], [`y=[$y1]`]. The point on the parabola is [`(1,[$y1])`].

This implies each point on the parabola of [`[$left]=[$right]`] is lower than the corresponding point on [`y=-x^{2}`]. This is why the parabola of [`[$left]=[$right]`] is thinner than the parabola of [`y=-x^{2}`]. 

[@ $radio->correct_ans() @]** is the correct answer.

END_PGML_SOLUTION

